The paper deals with computational social choice, which is a subfield of artificial intelligence and theoretical computer science. The focus is on the aggregation of preferences, which is a topic in game theory (cs.GT). The use of SMT solvers and higher-order logic suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the subfields of automated reasoning (cs.AI), logic in computer science (cs.LO), data structures and algorithms (cs.DS), and computational complexity (cs.CC).
